  "prompt": "How can I add a floating chart (like freezing top row) in Excel 2013?",
  "response": "In Excel, if you want to create a \"floating\" chart or make it stay in view while you scroll, you can't directly freeze a chart like you would freeze the top row of data. However, you can use a workaround by placing the chart in a convenient location so it remains visible while you scroll.\n\n### Here\u2019s how to create a floating effect for your chart:\n\n1. **Insert Chart**:\n   - Create your chart as you normally would by selecting your data and going to the `Insert` tab, then choosing a chart type.\n\n2. **Position the Chart**:\n   - After creating the chart, drag it to a suitable position, preferably near the top of your worksheet.\n\n3. **Use Split Panes**:\n   - Instead of freezing panes (which applies to rows/columns), you can use the \"Split\" feature. Here's how:\n     - Go to the `View` tab.\n     - Click on `Split`. This will divide your worksheet into different sections.\n     - Adjust the split by dragging the divider to fit where you want your view to change.\n\n4. **Resize and Arrange**:\n   - Resize your chart and rearrange your data in a way that keeps the chart easily visible in the split view.\n\n5. **Adjust Visibility**:\n   - If your chart is covered by data when scrolling, consider moving your data below the chart or adjusting the layout of your worksheet.\n\n### Regularly Update the Chart:\nIf your data changes and you need to update the chart, remember that the chart will still reflect updated data as long as it\u2019s linked to your data series.\n\nWhile this may not 'freeze' the chart in the exact way as you freeze rows or columns, it allows you to keep your chart visible while you scroll through other data in your spreadsheet. \n\nUsing these methods, you can ensure your chart remains visible while you work on other parts of your Excel sheet!",
